# Logging Standards

## Logger — Not console.log
Never use `console.log` directly. Use the project logger at `@/utils/logger`.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
console.log("player joined", playerId);

// ✅ GOOD
import { logger } from "@/utils/logger";
logger.info("Player joined", { playerId, roomId });
```

## Log Levels
| Level | Use For | Production |
|-------|---------|------------|
| `error` | Unrecoverable failures, exceptions | ON |
| `warn` | Recoverable issues, degraded state | ON |
| `info` | Key lifecycle events (join, leave, round start) | ON |
| `debug` | State changes, decision logic, flow tracing | OFF |
| `trace` | Per-frame data, hot-path details | OFF |

## Rules
- Every log entry must include **structured context** (object, not string interpolation)
- Never log PII (emails, IPs, real names) — use player IDs only
- Log at function boundaries: entry with params, exit with result/duration
- Performance-critical paths use `debug`/`trace` so they're silent in production
- Include `{ system: "combat" }` or similar tags for filtering

## Production Toggle
The logger respects a `LOG_LEVEL` environment variable. Default: `info` in production, `debug` in development.

```typescript
// Logger implementation pattern
export const logger = createLogger({
  level: import.meta.env.PROD ? "info" : "debug",
});
```

## What to Log
- Game lifecycle: room created, player joined/left, round start/end
- State transitions: territory claimed, border conflict resolved, player absorbed
- Errors: with full context and stack traces
- Performance: frame budget exceeded, network latency spikes (as `warn`)

## What NOT to Log
- Per-frame game loop ticks (unless `trace` level)
- Redundant success messages for routine operations
- Sensitive data (tokens, credentials, PII)
